    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks. so if the acidity is what causes the fatigue, does that mean the body has a way to get rid of it? how does the lactate actually leave the muscle?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The body does have a mechanism to remove excess lactic acid from the muscles. After intense exercise, the lactic acid is transported from the muscles to the bloodstream via a process called facilitated diffusion. The lactic acid is then carried to the liver, where it's converted back into glucose and released into the bloodstream. This glucose can then be used by the muscles or other tissues for energy. The liver also has another mechanism to remove excess lactic acid, which is through the production of bicarbonate ions. The bicarbonate ions can help neutralize the acidity of the lactic acid, making it less irritating to the muscles. This process is often referred to as the \"lactic acid buffering system.\"",
      "source": "target",
